Preheat your oven to 220°C. Chop the @new potatoes{1%salad potato} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel!). Pop the chunks on a low sided wide #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, then season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer. Bring a #saucepan{} of water to the boil.

Once your oven is hot, roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. When the potatoes have 10 mins left, smash the potatoes with back of a #fork{}, turn them over in the oil and roast for the remaining time.

> Use two baking trays if necessary, you want the potatoes nicely spread out.

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{1%small handful} then chop in half. Pick the @tarragon{1/4%handful}(leaves picked and roughly chopped) leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Fill and boil your #kettle{}, then pour the @water{150%ml} into a #measuring jug{} with the @vegetable stock powder{1}.

When you've just crushed your potatoes and popped back in the oven, pat the @hake fillets{2} dry with #kitchen paper{} and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Heat a splash of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the pan is hot, add the fish. Fry for ~{3-4%minutes}. Then, carefully turn and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} more.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

Remove the hake from the pan, set aside and cover with #foil{} to keep warm. Keep the pan - we'll use it again! Meanwhile, pop the green beans in a pan of boiling water. Cook for ~{4%minutes}, then drain in a #colander{}.

Once the hake is out of your frying pan, add the stock to your pan on medium-high heat. Boil until it has reduced by one-third, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove from the heat, then add the @sour cream{75%g} and tarragon. Give it a good stir and heat until piping hot. Season to taste with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed.

Divide the roasted crushed new potatoes and green beans between your plates. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Serve alongside the hake and finish with a generous amount of tarragon sauce. Enjoy!